BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Early Japanese Families in Ontario
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260511T180000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260511T190000
UID:69ce735f5c04bc0fc0611d6a@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:While most early Japanese immigrants to Canada settled on the 
 west coast\, a few made Ontario their homes. This lecture by Toronto genea
 logist\, Janice Nickerson\, tells the stories of eight Japanese families w
 ho lived in Ontario (mostly Toronto) before 1910\, the businesses they ran
 \, and the records she used to discover them\, including census\, civil re
 gistration\, city directories\, passenger lists\, newspapers and the recor
 ds of the Office of the Custodian of Enemy Property.
LOCATION:North York Central Library\, Room 2/3
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69ce735f5c04bc0fc0611d6a
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
