BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:What Our Buildings Say About Us: The History of Architecture in On
 tario
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260415T190000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260415T200000
UID:69a60798491b809c6f1da20e@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Professor Shannon Kyles discusses the history of Ontario’s a
 rchitecture and what it says about the people who have built this province
 . She will explore the early architecture of Indigenous peoples\, their fi
 rst contact with Europeans\, the 20\nth\ncentury wars and their resulting 
 democratic policies\, and finally the 21\nst\ncentury’s speculative hous
 ing market that we live in today.\nKyles is the author of ​"\nStory of O
 ntario Architecture: What We Built and Why We Built It\n". She has written
  and published articles on architecture\, taught History of Ontario archit
 ecture for 42 years at Mohawk College and online for universities\, and ha
 s served on the board of the Architectural Conservancy of Ontario for 15 y
 ears.\nStory of Ontario Architecture: What We Built and Why We Built It
LOCATION:Deer Park\, Room 204
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a60798491b809c6f1da20e
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Coffee and Conversation *LOCATION CHANGE*
