BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Bird Sounds: Understand Your Feathered Neighbours
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T130000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T143000
UID:69a73f984dacf581ff7f5cae@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Listen to the sounds of spring! Join us for an interactive pre
 sentation about how birds communicate. Enjoy interesting bird songs\, call
 s and more\, and learn some tips to remember them!\nPresented by the\nToro
 nto and Region Conservation Authority (TRCA)\n.\nTalk is friendly for all 
 ages but geared towards youth and adults.\nRegister online. Drop-ins also 
 welcome.\nThis program is part of TPL's\nOur Fragile Planet\nprogram serie
 s\, supported by Friends of Toronto Public Library\, South Chapter.​\nIn
 formation Collection Notice:\nThe personal information on this form is col
 lected by the Toronto Public Library under the Public Libraries Act\, sect
 ions 20(a)\, 20(c)\, and 20(d). The information will only be used for even
 t and program registration\, delivery and evaluation. Questions about how 
 the library handles your information can be directed to Answerline staff a
 t\nanswerline@tpl.ca\n\, 416-397-5981\, 789 Yonge Street\, Toronto ON M4W 
 2G8.
LOCATION:S. Walter Stewart\, Auditorium
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a73f984dacf581ff7f5cae
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Creating a Minimum Viable Product or Service Offering
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260416T190000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260416T200000
UID:69b83109567ba1dd31fd7e2e@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Lily Akagbosu\, Newcomer Entrepreneur in Residence\nMany entre
 preneurs believe they need a perfect product before launching their busine
 ss. In reality\, the most successful founders start with a simple first ve
 rsion that allows them to learn quickly and improve over time.\nIn this se
 ssion\, we’ll explore how to create a Minimum Viable Product (MVP) or ea
 rly service offering that allows you to start small while gathering valuab
 le feedback from customers. Whether you’re building a digital or physica
 l product\, or offering a service-based business\, you’ll learn practica
 l ways to launch with minimal time\, cost\, and complexity. By the end of 
 the workshop\, you’ll have a clearer plan for bringing your idea to life
  and testing it in the real world.\nRegistration is required.\nThis progra
 m is part of Toronto Public Library’s\nNewcomer Entrepreneur in Residenc
 e\nprogram series and\nNewcomer Entrepreneurship Initiative\n\, designed t
 o support newcomers as they explore entrepreneurship and build practical s
 mall business skills. Participants will learn about key topics for startin
 g and growing a business in Canada\, with guidance from an experienced ent
 repreneur in residence. For more information and a full list of programs\,
  visit\ntpl.ca/eir\n.\nLily Akagbos\nu\nis a Product Manager and entrepren
 eur with a Master’s degree in Digital Product Management from Queen’s 
 University. She has shaped and delivered products at organizations includi
 ng IBM\, Shopify\, and the Bank of Montreal. Beyond her product work\, she
  has built hands-on business experience through startup ventures\, commerc
 e\, and consulting. Over the years\, Lily has actively engaged in Canada
 ’s entrepreneurship ecosystem through the University of Toronto’s Blac
 k Founders Network\, Venture for Canada\, ventureLAB\, and NEXT Canada. Sh
 e supports entrepreneurs and aspiring business owners from idea through la
 unch and growth\, and delivers talks on leadership and innovation.\nInform
 ation Collection Notice:\nThe personal information on this form is collect
 ed by the Toronto Public Library under the Public Libraries Act\, sections
  20(a)\, 20(c)\, and 20(d). The information will only be used for event an
 d program registration\, delivery and evaluation. Questions about how the 
 library handles your information can be directed to Answerline staff at\na
 nswerline@tpl.ca\n\, 416-397-5981\, 789 Yonge Street\, Toronto ON M4W 2G8.
LOCATION:Deer Park\, Room 204
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69b83109567ba1dd31fd7e2e
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Ciné-club / French Film Club: Monsieur Lazhar
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260417T180000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260417T200000
UID:69b98b754dacf581ff828e41@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Rejoignez-nous pour une présentation de\nMonsieur Lazhar\n(20
 11)\, réalisée par Philippe Falardeau. Ce film raconte l’histoire d’
 un réfugié politique\, nouvellement engagé comme professeur dans une é
 cole Montréalaise dévastée par la mort d’une enseignante. Une discus
 sion conviviale en français suivra le film\, si le temps le permet. Film
  en version originale\, sous-titré en anglais.\nAucune réservation requi
 se.\nCette projection est organisée en collaboration avec ReelCanada\, da
 ns le cadre de la Journée du cinéma canadien.\nJoin us for a French-lang
 uage film screening of\nMonsieur Lazhar\n(2011)\, directed by Philippe Fal
 ardeau. This film tells the story of a political refugee hired to replace 
 a recently deceased teacher at a grieving Montreal school. An informal di
 scussion in French to follow the film\, time permitting. Film presented wi
 th English subtitles.\nDrop in.\nThis screening is presented in collaborat
 ion with ReelCanada as part of National Canadian Film Day.\nAccessibilité
 :\nLe sous-titrage en direct ou automatique\, l’interprétation en langu
 e des signes\, les services d’intervenant\, ou les services d’accompag
 nement sont disponibles sur demande. Veuillez soumettre votre demande au 
 moins deux semaines à l’avance à : tpl.ca/accessibility-events
LOCATION:S. Walter Stewart\, Meeting Room
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69b98b754dacf581ff828e41
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Japanese Tea Ceremony
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260504T130000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260504T140000
UID:69ab63e14a9fd98b7f82a4a8@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Experience the traditional art of the Japanese tea ceremony.  
 Learn about Japanese culture and the important philosophy behind the tea c
 eremony. This presentation not only offers a demonstration of traditional 
 Matcha preparation using authentic tools\, but zen philosophies which may 
 also apply to daily life. Discover how Matcha is harvested\, its history\,
  how to make/use it\, how to differenciate between different grades\, and 
 how to conserve it.\nReina Sakao is a fourth-generation tea house and Uras
 enke tea instructor who trained at the Urasenke School in Japan where her 
 family owns and operates a tea plantation in Shizuoka. Reina has over 10 y
 ears of experience with the Japanese tea ceremony (second-degree Urasenke 
 tea ceremony instructor).​\nInformation Collection Notice:\nThe personal
  information on this form is collected by the Toronto Public Library under
  the Public Libraries Act\, sections 20(a)\, 20(c)\, and 20(d). The inform
 ation will only be used for event and program registration\, delivery and 
 evaluation. Questions about how the library handles your information can b
 e directed to Answerline staff at\nanswerline@tpl.ca\n\, 416-397-5981\, 78
 9 Yonge Street\, Toronto ON M4W 2G8.
LOCATION:Barbara Frum\, Located in Room B on the third floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69ab63e14a9fd98b7f82a4a8
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Birding 101: Tips for Bird Watching in Toronto
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260527T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260527T193000
UID:69da85f5213814b1b5239f49@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Learn everything you need to know to start birding in your own
  backyard!\nBirding is fun\, easy\, and can be done anywhere\, from your 
 own backyard to a local park. Get expert tips on choosing binoculars and
  field guides\, when and where to bird in your neighbourhood or in the ci
 ty\, and how to identify the birds you are likely to find. Find out about
  clubs and field trips\, birding ethics\, and protection and conservation 
 efforts. Presented by Monika Croydon\, a member of the Toronto Ornithologi
 cal Club.\nAll are welcome. Drop-in\, no registration necessary.
LOCATION:Danforth/Coxwell\, 2nd Floor Program Room
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69da85f5213814b1b5239f49
