BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Digital Life Skills for Seniors: Online Safety
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260414T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260414T153000
UID:699f2bd35506be0745fef523@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:For people who have basic internet skills but want to learn ab
 out the online safety and privacy. We will cover tips for creating secure 
 passwords\, using public Wi-Fi safely\, protecting your device from malwar
 e\, and how to recognize online scams.\nRegistration is required. Please r
 egister online or call the branch at 416-393-7700. Space is limited.\nInfo
 rmation Collection Notice:\nThe personal information on this form is colle
 cted by the Toronto Public Library under the Public Libraries Act\, sectio
 ns 20(a)\, 20(c)\, and 20(d). The information will only be used for event 
 and program registration\, delivery and evaluation. Questions about how th
 e library handles your information can be directed to Answerline staff at\
 nanswerline@tpl.ca\n\, 416-397-5981\, 789 Yonge Street\, Toronto ON M4W 2G
 8.
LOCATION:Main Street\, Basement Program Room
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/699f2bd35506be0745fef523
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Youth Hub: Flower Arrangements
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260416T153000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260416T190000
UID:69d69ed2dcd22510c03be6e5@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Create beautiful flower bouquets! Welcome in the spring season
  with floral creating/designing. All materials provided.\nThis program is
  part of Youth Hub service. Youth Hubs are a welcoming place for teens aft
 er school and in the summer\, where helpful staff are always available. F
 ree\, nutritious snacks are offered daily. Drop by a branch with a\nYouth
  Hub\nor call the branch to find out more.
LOCATION:Parkdale\, Youth Hub Auditorium
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69d69ed2dcd22510c03be6e5
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Instagram Poetry Workshop
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260530T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260530T160000
UID:699f35b2d34a4e759286f0e2@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Marc Nair\, a poet from Singapore\, has published 11 collecti
 ons of poetry and has been featured in numerous anthologies both print and
  online. A seasoned poetry slammer\, he has performed spoken word for ove
 r ten years in more than ten countries and has represented Singapore in in
 ternational poetry slam competitions.\nIn this creative writing workshop\,
  Marc will teach participants what makes an IG poem stand out and its pl
 ayful blend of words\, visuals\, and emotion. Together\, we’ll break dow
 n the form\, dive into inspiring examples\, and uncover how poets are tran
 sforming social media into a canvas for storytelling.\nYou’ll get the ch
 ance to craft your own Instagram‑style poems\, experimenting with text t
 o create special pieces. Share your work\, get inspired by others\, and le
 ave with fresh ways to bring poetry into the digital age.\nInformation Col
 lection Notice:\nThe personal information on this form is collected by the
  Toronto Public Library under the Public Libraries Act\, sections 20(a)\, 
 20(c)\, and 20(d). The information will only be used for event and program
  registration\, delivery and evaluation. Questions about how the library h
 andles your information can be directed to Answerline staff at\nanswerline
 @tpl.ca\n\, 416-397-5981\, 789 Yonge Street\, Toronto ON M4W 2G8.
LOCATION:Malvern\, Community Room
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/699f35b2d34a4e759286f0e2
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Live Music: Thompson Egbo-Egbo Trio
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260413T190000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260413T200000
UID:699f36d12866a5b4883e48b3@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:The Thompson Egbo-Egbo Trio brings a fresh and compelling voic
 e to Toronto’s jazz scene\, blending elegance\, groove\, and adventurous
  improvisation.\nLed by pianist and composer\nThompson Egbo-Egbo\n\, with\
 nRandall Hall\non bass and\nJeff Halischuck\non drums\, the trio creates d
 ynamic performances that balance rich harmony\, deep rhythmic interplay\, 
 and storytelling that resonates far beyond the final note.\nDrop in progra
 m. No registration required.\nFor more information\, please contact the Ar
 ts Department at 416-393-7157.\n**\nAccessibility at Toronto Public Librar
 y:\nToronto Public Library is committed to accessibility. Please call or e
 mail us if you are Deaf or have a disability and would like to request acc
 ommodation to participate in this program. Please let us know as far in ad
 vance as possible and we will do our best to meet your request. At least t
 hree weeks notice is preferred. Phone 416-393-7099 or email accessibleserv
 ices@tpl.ca.
LOCATION:Toronto Reference Library\, Beeton Hall
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/699f36d12866a5b4883e48b3
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Japanese Tea Ceremony
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260523T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260523T150000
UID:699f392e8089f23c675e1e63@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Experience the traditional art of the Japanese tea ceremony.  
 Learn about Japanese culture and the important philosophy behind the tea c
 eremony. This presentation not only offers a demonstration of traditional 
 Matcha preparation using authentic tools\, but zen philosophies which may 
 also apply to daily life. Discover how Matcha is harvested\, its history\,
  how to make/use it\, how to differenciate between different grades\, and 
 how to conserve it.\nReina Sakao is a fourth-generation tea house and Uras
 enke tea instructor who trained at the Urasenke School in Japan where her 
 family owns and operates a tea plantation in Shizuoka. Reina has over 10 y
 ears of experience with the Japanese tea ceremony (first-degree Urasenke t
 ea ceremony instructor).​
LOCATION:Agincourt\, Main Program Room
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/699f392e8089f23c675e1e63
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
