BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Elamin Abdelmahmoud\, Stephen Marche & Tanya Talaga: On Canada
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260414T190000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260414T200000
UID:69a0ae94b0595799c09f99c5@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Elamin Abdelmahmoud\, Stephen Marche and Tanya Talaga discuss 
 the future of Canadian identity and sovereignty.\nAt an unprecedented mome
 nt in the nation's history\, Canadians across the country are responding t
 o escalating threats to their sovereignty with a crescendo of national sol
 idarity.\nFrom proudly celebrating CanCon to "buying Canadian\," citizens 
 are finding big and small ways to make statements of resistance to the thr
 eats of tariffs\, annexation and more being levied by their closest neighb
 our.\nBut with this swelling show of national pride come pressing question
 s. What are the key economic and cultural implications of the U.S. governm
 ent's growing hostility? With such a long history of partnership between t
 he two countries\, how can Canada most strategically position itself amids
 t changing political tides? How do we best meet this moment\, as individua
 ls and as a country?\nElamin Abdelmahmoud\, Stephen Marche and Tanya Talag
 a speak with journalist Michelle Shephard about some of the most urgent is
 sues affecting Canada's political\, economic and cultural landscape today.
 \nAbout this event’s guests:\nElamin Abdelmahmoud\nStephen Marche\nTanya
  Talaga\nMichelle Shephard\nRead more:\nElbows Up!\nThe Next Civil War\nTh
 e Knowing\n***\nPLAN YOUR VISIT:\nLocation:\nConcourse Event Space\, North
  York Central Library (5120 Yonge St)\nTime:\nDoors open 6:00pm\, Event st
 arts 7:00pm.\nTickets:\nFree registration required.\nTicket policy:\nWe ov
 ersell these events to ensure that the greatest number of people have an o
 pportunity to attend. Tickets guaranteed until 6:45pm or until capacity is
  reached. Seating first come\, first served.\n***\nThis event is part of o
 ur signature\nSalon Series\n\, where we host local and international autho
 rs\, artists and thinkers in conversation about their new books and big id
 eas.\nIt is also part of our\nOn Civil Society\nseries\, where we host lo
 cal and international authors\, activists and academics in conversation ab
 out the most critical topics of our time. Generously supported by the McCo
 nnell Foundation and also by Chris M. Reid.\n***\nInformation Collection N
 otice:\nThe personal information on this form is collected by the Toronto 
 Public Library under the Public Libraries Act\, sections 20(a)\, 20(c)\, a
 nd 20(d). The information will only be used for event and program registra
 tion\, delivery and evaluation. Registrants may be contacted to fill out a
  brief survey following the program. Questions about how the library handl
 es your information can be directed to Answerline staff at answerline@tpl.
 ca\, 416-397-5981\, 789 Yonge Street\, Toronto ON M4W 2G8.
LOCATION:North York Central Library\, Concourse Event Space
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a0ae94b0595799c09f99c5
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:A Field Guide to Birds of Ontario
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260421T190000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260421T200000
UID:69a0aec88b29ea2800d2b318@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:ROM's Mark Peck and biologist Emily Rondel take us on a tour t
 hrough the diversity of bird species found in Ontario.\nFrom watching the 
 soaring Red-tailed Hawk to hearing the haunting call of the Common Loon\, 
 birds are our daily connection to nature.\nA Field Guide to Birds of Ontar
 io\noffers detailed descriptions of migrant and resident Ontario bird spec
 ies and accidentals\, including notes on appearance\, sound\, habitat\, an
 d breeding.\nMark Peck and Emily Rondel speak with author Kyo Maclear abou
 t their essential companion for the nature enthusiast and about how birds 
 add beauty to every corner of our lives\, from the most built-up inner cit
 y to the most remote forest\, reminding us that we are part of nature\, no
  matter where we are.\nQ&A and book signing to follow. Books available for
  purchase.\nIn collaboration with the Royal Ontario Museum.\nAbout this ev
 ent’s guests:\nMark Peck\nEmily Rondel\nKyo Maclear\nRead more:\nA Field
  Guide to Birds of Ontario\nToronto's Birds\nBirds Art Life\n***\nPLAN YOU
 R VISIT:\nLocation:\nBeeton Hall\, Toronto Reference Library (789 Yonge St
 reet)\, 1st floor\nTime:\nDoors open 6:00pm\, Event starts 7:00pm.\nTicket
 s:\nFree registration required.\nTicket policy:\nWe oversell these events 
 to ensure that the greatest number of people have an opportunity to attend
 . Tickets guaranteed until 6:45pm or until capacity is reached. Seating fi
 rst come\, first served.\n***\nThis event is part of our signature\nSalon 
 Series\n\, where we host local and international authors\, artists and thi
 nkers in conversation about their new books and big ideas.\n***\nInformati
 on Collection Notice:\nThe personal information on this form is collected 
 by the Toronto Public Library under the Public Libraries Act\, sections 20
 (a)\, 20(c)\, and 20(d). The information will only be used for event and p
 rogram registration\, delivery and evaluation. Registrants may be contacte
 d to fill out a brief survey following the program. Questions about how th
 e library handles your information can be directed to Answerline staff at 
 answerline@tpl.ca\, 416-397-5981\, 789 Yonge Street\, Toronto ON M4W 2G8.
LOCATION:Toronto Reference Library\, Beeton Hall\, 1st floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a0aec88b29ea2800d2b318
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
