BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Live\, from the Appel Salon! It's Susan Morrison & Paul Myers
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260427T190000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260427T200000
UID:69a0bb578089f23c675e73c3@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:For half a century\, the Toronto-born Lorne Michaels has been 
 the revered\, feared\, and irreplaceable visionary behind the most influen
 tial comedy series in the world:\nSaturday Night Live\n. Winner of more th
 an one-hundred Emmy Awards\, Michaels has helmed the series through its me
 teoric rise\, countless setbacks\, and relentless reinventions. No one in 
 comedy has a keener eye for talent – the household names to whom Michael
 s has given a start are too many to mention – or a more ruthless work et
 hic.\nIn\nLorne: The Man Who Invented Saturday Night Live\n\, Susan Morris
 on has written the first definitive biography of this elusive genius. With
  unprecedented access to Michaels and the entire\nSNL\napparatus\, Morriso
 n takes readers behind the curtain for the story of how Michaels created a
 nd maintained the institution that changed comedy forever. In conversation
  with author Paul Myers\, Morrison will take the audience on a mesmerizing
  inside tour of a singular obsessive whose taste still determines the cour
 se of modern comedy.\nABOUT THIS EVENT'S GUESTS:\nSusan Morrison\nis the a
 rticles editor of\nThe New Yorker.\nShe is the former editor in chief of t
 he\nNew York Observer\nand an original editor of\nSPY\nmagazine. She lives
  in New York City.\nPaul Myers\nis a Canadian writer and musician living i
 n Berkeley\, California. His most recent book is\nJohn Candy: A Life in Co
 medy\n\, and his previous books include\nThe Kids in the Hall: One Dumb Gu
 y\n\, which was the source for the Canadian Screen Award–winning documen
 tary\nThe Kids in the Hall: Comedy Punks\nfrom Amazon Studios\, on which h
 e served as executive producer\; the critically acclaimed\nA Wizard a True
  Star: Todd Rundgren in the Studio\n\;\nIt Ain’t Easy: Long John Baldry 
 and the Birth of the British Blues\n\; and\nBarenaked Ladies: Public Stunt
 s\, Private Stories\n.\n***\nThis event is part of our signature\nSalon Se
 ries\n\, where we host local and international authors\, artists and think
 ers in conversation about their new books and big ideas.\n***\nPLAN YOUR V
 ISIT:\nLocation:\nBram and Bluma Appel Salon\, Toronto Reference Library (
 789 Yonge Street)\, 2nd floor\nTime:\nDoors open 6:00pm\, Event starts 7:0
 0pm.\nTickets:\nFree registration required.\nTicket policy:\nWe oversell t
 hese events to make sure that the greatest number of people have an opport
 unity to attend. Tickets are guaranteed until 6:45pm or until capacity is 
 reached. Any remaining space will be opened up to the rush line beginning 
 at 6:45pm. Seating first come\, first served. Tickets do not guarantee sea
 ts.\nAccessibility:\nTPL is committed to accessibility. If you are Deaf or
  have a disability and would like to request accommodation for this event\
 , please contact accessibleservices@tpl.ca or 416-393-7099 at least three 
 weeks prior to the event.\n***\nInformation Collection Notice:\nThe person
 al information on this form is collected by the Toronto Public Library und
 er the Public Libraries Act\, sections 20(a)\, 20(c)\, and 20(d). The info
 rmation will only be used for event and program registration\, delivery an
 d evaluation.\nRegistrants may be contacted to fill out a brief survey fol
 lowing the program\n. Questions about how the library handles your informa
 tion can be directed to Answerline staff at answerline@tpl.ca\, 416-397-59
 81\, 789 Yonge Street\, Toronto ON M4W 2G8.
LOCATION:Toronto Reference Library\, Bram and Bluma Appel Salon\, 2nd Floo
 r
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a0bb578089f23c675e73c3
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
