BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Parallel Paths: the Chinese and Jewish Communities in The Ward and
  Beyond
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260512T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260512T193000
UID:69a0bbdc491b809c6f1cbf0d@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:The civic narratives of Toronto’s Chinese and Jewish communi
 ties have overlapped since the days of The Ward in the early 20th century\
 , through to the present day. In this unique discussion\, aided by artefac
 ts from the Chinese Canadian Archive\, historian and author Arlene Chan an
 d journalist John Lorinc will explore both the pleasure and the importance
  of cultural connection in the world’s most diverse metropolis.\nABOUT T
 HIS EVENT'S GUESTS:\nArlene Chan\nshares her passion for the history\, cul
 ture\, and traditions of the Chinese in Canada in her speaking engagements
 \, essays\, and books\, including\nThe Chinese in Toronto from 1878\n(2011
 ). With a long standing commitment to community work\, she currently serve
 s as the president of the Jean Lumb Foundation.\nJohn Lorinc\nis a Toronto
  freelance journalist who writes about cities\, business\, immigration and
  local history for a range of publications\, including\nThe Globe and Mail
 \, the Toronto Star\nand\nSpacing\n. John co-edited\nThe Ward: The Life an
 d Loss of Toronto’s First Immigrant Neighbourhood\n\, and\nThe Ward Unco
 vered: The Archaeology of Everyday Life\n. He is also the author of\nNo Je
 ws Live Here: A Memoir\n(Coach House Books\, 2024).\n***\nThis event is pa
 rt of our signature\nSalon Series\n\, where we host local and internationa
 l authors\, artists and thinkers in conversation about their new books and
  big ideas.\n***\nPLAN YOUR VISIT:\nLocation:\nBeeton Hall\, Toronto Refer
 ence Library (789 Yonge Street)\, 1st floor\nTime:\nDoors open 5:30pm\, Ev
 ent starts 6:30pm.\nTickets:\nFree registration required.\nTicket policy:\
 nWe oversell these events to make sure that the greatest number of people 
 have an opportunity to attend. Tickets are guaranteed until 6:45pm or unti
 l capacity is reached. Any remaining space will be opened up to the rush l
 ine beginning at 6:45pm. Seating first come\, first served. Tickets do not
  guarantee seats.\nAccessibility:\nTPL is committed to accessibility. If y
 ou are Deaf or have a disability and would like to request accommodation f
 or this event\, please contact accessibleservices@tpl.ca or 416-393-7099 a
 t least three weeks prior to the event.\n***\nInformation Collection Notic
 e:\nThe personal information on this form is collected by the Toronto Publ
 ic Library under the Public Libraries Act\, sections 20(a)\, 20(c)\, and 2
 0(d). The information will only be used for event and program registration
 \, delivery and evaluation.\nRegistrants may be contacted to fill out a br
 ief survey following the program\n. Questions about how the library handle
 s your information can be directed to Answerline staff at answerline@tpl.c
 a\, 416-397-5981\, 789 Yonge Street\, Toronto ON M4W 2G8.
LOCATION:Toronto Reference Library\, Beeton Hall\, 1st Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a0bbdc491b809c6f1cbf0d
