BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Judy Blume\, A Life: Mark Oppenheimer & Molly Ringwald
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260519T190000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260519T200000
UID:69a0bd051e64afd01e5e567d@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Are you there\, God? It's us\, fans of Judy Blume\, eagerly an
 ticipating a definitive biography of the legendary young adult novelist. N
 ow\, with unprecedented access to papers\, correspondence\, and the author
  herself\, acclaimed biographer Mark Oppenheimer has provided just that: a
  beautiful\, multidimensional portrait\, and the first authorized biograph
 y of Judy Blume. Oppenheimer goes deep\, exploring Blume's middle-class 19
 50s upbringing\, complicated childhood\, varied relationships and marriage
 s\, unabashed sexual experiences\, bouts of heartache and loss\, and endur
 ing legacy as a champion of free speech and contemporary literature. Oppen
 heimer peels back the curtain to reveal the woman behind the literary empi
 re in all her complex\, multifaceted glory – a true gift for anyone who 
 grew up reading and loving these extraordinary books.\nIn this once-in-a-l
 ifetime event\, memoirist\, translator\, actor\, and avowed Judy Blume fan
 atic Molly Ringwald hosts a conversation with Mark Oppenheimer about the r
 eal woman behind the iconic persona\, and the unlikely journey of her lite
 rary ascension.\nABOUT THIS EVENT'S GUESTS:\nMark Oppenheimer\nhas been co
 vering American religion for 25 years. He holds a Ph.D. in religious studi
 es from Yale\, and has taught at Stanford\, Wesleyan\, Wellesley\, NYU\, B
 oston College\, and Yale\, where he was the founding director of the Yale 
 Journalism Initiative. From 2010 to 2016\, he wrote the "Beliefs" column\,
  about religion\, for\nThe New York Times\n\, and he has also written for 
 publications including\nThe New Yorker\, The Nation\, GQ\, Slate\,\nand ma
 ny more. He created\nUnorthodox\n\, the world's most popular podcast about
  Jewish life and culture\, with over 7 million downloads to date. More rec
 ently\, he hosted an eight-part podcast called\nGatecrashers\n\, about the
  history of Jews and antisemitism at Ivy League schools. He is the author 
 of five books\, including\nThe Newish Jewish Encyclopedia\nand\, most rece
 ntly\,\nSquirrel Hill: The Tree of Life Synagogue Shooting and the Soul of
  a Neighborhood\n. He lives in Connecticut with his wife\, four daughters\
 , one son\, and two dogs.\nMolly Ringwald\nis an actor\, translator\, and 
 author. She has published two bestselling books\,\nGetting the Pretty Back
 \nand\nWhen It Happens to You\n\, and translated the award-winning bestsel
 ling French novel\nLie With Me\nby Philippe Besson and the memoir\nMy Cous
 in Maria Schneider\nby Vanessa Schneider. Her essays have appeared in the\
 nNew York Times\n\,\nThe New Yorker\n\,\nVogue\n\,\nMarie-Claire\n\, and\n
 The Guardian\n. Her extensive film credits include Paul Mazursky's\nTempes
 t\n\, the iconic John Hughes films\nSixteen Candles\n\,\nPretty in Pink\n\
 , and\nThe Breakfast Club\n\, the indie film\nAll These Small Moments\,\na
 nd Netflix’s\nThe Kissing Booth\n.\n***\nThis event is part of our signa
 ture\nSalon Series\n\, where we host local and international authors\, art
 ists and thinkers in conversation about their new books and big ideas.\n**
 *\nPLAN YOUR VISIT:\nLocation:\nBram and Bluma Appel Salon\, Toronto Refer
 ence Library (789 Yonge Street)\, 2nd floor\nTime:\nDoors open 6:00pm\, Ev
 ent starts 7:00pm.\nTickets:\nFree registration required.\nTicket policy:\
 nWe oversell these events to make sure that the greatest number of people 
 have an opportunity to attend. Tickets are guaranteed until 6:45pm or unti
 l capacity is reached. Any remaining space will be opened up to the rush l
 ine beginning at 6:45pm. Seating first come\, first served. Tickets do not
  guarantee seats.\nAccessibility:\nTPL is committed to accessibility. If y
 ou are Deaf or have a disability and would like to request accommodation f
 or this event\, please contact accessibleservices@tpl.ca or 416-393-7099 a
 t least three weeks prior to the event.\n***\nInformation Collection Notic
 e:\nThe personal information on this form is collected by the Toronto Publ
 ic Library under the Public Libraries Act\, sections 20(a)\, 20(c)\, and 2
 0(d). The information will only be used for event and program registration
 \, delivery and evaluation.\nRegistrants may be contacted to fill out a br
 ief survey following the program\n. Questions about how the library handle
 s your information can be directed to Answerline staff at answerline@tpl.c
 a\, 416-397-5981\, 789 Yonge Street\, Toronto ON M4W 2G8.
LOCATION:Toronto Reference Library\, Bram and Bluma Appel Salon\, 2nd Floo
 r
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a0bd051e64afd01e5e567d
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
