BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:NatureTO: Managing Invasive Plants Around Your Home
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260414T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260414T153000
UID:69a1cd196724c63d00f5953a@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Join the\nCity of Toronto Urban Forestry\nteam\nfor a presenta
 tion on invasive plants commonly found around homes in Toronto. Learn how 
 to identify these species\, understand their impact\, and how to manage th
 em. You’ll also get tips on supporting local biodiversity through enhanc
 ing native habitats. Perfect for gardeners\, homeowners\, and anyone inter
 ested in urban ecology.\nDROP-IN!\nNo registration required\nThis program 
 is part of TPL's\nOur Fragile Planet\nprogram series\, supported by Friend
 s of Toronto Public Library\, South Chapter.​
LOCATION:Rexdale
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a1cd196724c63d00f5953a
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Mad Science Workshop - Bugs!
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260605T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260605T150000
UID:69a1d9706724c63d00f59721@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Explore the world of arthropods! Children examine insect anato
 my up close and classify creepy crawlers into insects and non-insects. At 
 habitat stations\, they build insect puzzles\, discover how insects see\, 
 spread pollen\, and defend themselves\, and uncover the science behind the
 se fascinating creatures. Also\, you can take home a model insect!\nFor sc
 hool-age children (5-12) and their caregivers. Drop-in.\nUnfortunately\, w
 e cannot accommodate any large groups/daycares at this time.\nIf you or yo
 ur child lives with a disability\, and requires an accessibility accommoda
 tion to participate in this program\, please contact Accessibility Service
 s by email\naccessibleservices@tpl.ca\n\, or voicemail\, 416-393-7099\, to
  make a request. Please contact us at least three weeks in advance.
LOCATION:Jones\, Children's Area
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a1d9706724c63d00f59721
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:The Japanese Tea Ceremony
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260505T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260505T150000
UID:69a1e0cf1e64afd01e5e879e@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Experience the traditional art of the Japanese tea ceremony.
   Learn about Japanese culture and the important philosophy behind the t
 ea ceremony. This presentation not only offers a demonstration of tradi
 tional Matcha preparation using authentic tools\, but zen philosophies w
 hich may also apply to daily life.\nDiscover how Matcha is harvested\, i
 ts history\, how to make/use it\, how to differentiate between different
  grades\, and how to conserve it.\nReina Sakao is a fourth-generation tea
  house and Urasenke tea instructor who trained at the Urasenke School in J
 apan where her family owns and operates a tea plantation in Shizuoka. Rein
 a has over 10 years of experience with the Japanese tea ceremony (second-d
 egree Urasenke tea ceremony instructor).​
LOCATION:Taylor Memorial\, Meeting room
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a1e0cf1e64afd01e5e879e
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:History of Generative Music: The Baroque and Classical Eras
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260413T180000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260413T200000
UID:69a1feaf1e64afd01e5e905d@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:In the 1700s\, some of the world's most celebrated composers w
 ere experimenting with music that could compose itself. Techniques like mu
 sical dice games and rule-based composition turned music creation into a f
 ascinating blend of structure and chance - ideas that feel remarkably mode
 rn.\nIn this session\, you'll discover how composers from the Baroque and 
 Classical periods developed systems for generating music\, explore the mec
 hanisms that made these techniques work\, and learn how their ideas connec
 t directly to today's AI-powered music tools.\nDrop-in\, no registration r
 equired.\nThis program is part of the Innovator in Residence (AI and Music
  Production) program\, which is designed to help beginner and intermediate
  learners build knowledge and creative skills and get hands-on with curren
 t AI tools in music production and learn about the history\, copyright and
  ethics of generative music. For more information and a full list of progr
 ams\, visit tpl.ca/airesident.
LOCATION:Fairview\, Room 201\, 2nd Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a1feaf1e64afd01e5e905d
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:After School Club
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260525T160000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260525T170000
UID:69c44d175a2d780f42c4bb02@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Looking for something to do after school? Come out to our Afte
 r School Club and learn new things\, make stuff\, meet other kids and have
  fun!\nFor ages 6-12. DROP-IN!\nSnacks are offered during the After School
  Club for participants. Ingredient lists will be available. Snacks are gen
 erously supported\, in part\, by donors.
LOCATION:Rexdale
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69c44d175a2d780f42c4bb02
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Create a DJ Set with AI Tools for Teens
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T160000
UID:69a1ff7a491b809c6f1cfc8f@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Ever wonder how DJs create seamless mixes that keep a dance fl
 oor moving? What if you could build your own DJ set from scratch using art
 ificial intelligence?\nJoin us for a hands-on demonstration/workshop where
  you'll use AI to generate original beat-based music\, then learn how to b
 reak it down into stems\, loops\, and sections\, and then reassemble them 
 into a dynamic set you can perform live. No prior music or programming exp
 erience is required.\nRegistration is required.\nThis program is part of t
 he Innovator in Residence (AI and Music Production) program\, which is des
 igned to help beginner and intermediate learners build knowledge and creat
 ive skills and get hands-on with current AI tools in music production and 
 learn about the history\, copyright and ethics of generative music. For mo
 re information and a full list of programs\, visit tpl.ca/airesident.
LOCATION:Fairview\, Digital Innovation Hub\, 3rd Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a1ff7a491b809c6f1cfc8f
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Music Copyright and Ethics in the AI Era
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260424T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260424T160000
UID:69a2002c491b809c6f1cfcda@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:***Please note - the time of this program has changed. We apol
 ogize for any inconvenience.***\nWhen you use AI to create music\, who act
 ually owns it? Can a melody generated by a machine infringe on someone els
 e's copyright? As AI tools become more accessible\, these questions are mo
 re relevant than ever - and the answers aren't always straightforward.\nIn
  this session\, you'll get a plain-language breakdown of how music copyrig
 ht works\, what the rules are around sampling\, and how these long-standin
 g principles apply to AI-generated music. You'll also hear about landmark 
 legal cases - both surprising victories and cautionary tales - including r
 eal-world examples from a working composer's own career.\nDrop-in\, no reg
 istration required.\n***Please note - the time of this program has changed
 . We apologize for any inconvenience.***\nThis program is part of the Inno
 vator in Residence (AI and Music Production) program\, which is designed t
 o help beginner and intermediate learners build knowledge and creative ski
 lls and get hands-on with current AI tools in music production and learn a
 bout the history\, copyright and ethics of generative music. For more info
 rmation and a full list of programs\, visit tpl.ca/airesident.
LOCATION:Fairview\, Room 201\, 2nd Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a2002c491b809c6f1cfcda
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:History of Generative Music: The Early Modern Era
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260430T160000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260430T180000
UID:69a200ef1e64afd01e5e909d@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:The twentieth century brought radical new ideas about what mus
 ic could be - from compositions determined by coin tosses to pieces that r
 earranged themselves with every performance. Pioneering composers began us
 ing chance\, repetition\, and early electronics to challenge everything au
 diences thought they knew about music.\nIn this session\, you'll explore h
 ow early modern composers pushed the boundaries of generative music\, disc
 over the creative and technical mechanisms behind their experiments\, and 
 learn how their breakthroughs paved the way for the AI music tools we use 
 today.\nDrop-in\, no registration required.\nThis program is part of the I
 nnovator in Residence (AI and Music Production) program\, which is designe
 d to help beginner and intermediate learners build knowledge and creative 
 skills and get hands-on with current AI tools in music production and lear
 n about the history\, copyright and ethics of generative music. For more i
 nformation and a full list of programs\, visit\ntpl.ca/airesident\n.
LOCATION:Fairview\, Digital Innovation Hub\, 3rd Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a200ef1e64afd01e5e909d
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Create Hip-Hop Music with AI Tools for Teens
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260514T160000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260514T170000
UID:69a2019f8089f23c675eb003@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Have you ever had a melody stuck in your head and wished you c
 ould turn it into a real song? AI tools are making it easier than ever to 
 bring your musical experiences to life - but how do you make sure the musi
 c you create is truly yours?\nExplore how to use AI as a creative assistan
 t to build radio-ready hip-hop tracks based on your own original ideas. Yo
 u'll learn how to guide AI tools to serve your vision rather than replace 
 it\, and we'll cover Canadian copyright guidelines to ensure the music you
  make qualifies as your own intellectual property. No prior music or progr
 amming experience is required.\nThis program is part of the Innovator in R
 esidence (AI and Music Production) program\, which is designed to help beg
 inner and intermediate learners build knowledge and creative skills and ge
 t hands-on with current AI tools in music production and learn about the h
 istory\, copyright and ethics of generative music. For more information an
 d a full list of programs\, visit\ntpl.ca/airesident\n.
LOCATION:Fairview\, Youth Hub\, 3rd Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a2019f8089f23c675eb003
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:History of Generative Music: The Last 50 Years
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260516T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260516T160000
UID:69a201c84dacf581ff7e6743@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:From the first computer-generated compositions to the AI music
  tools available today\, the past five decades have seen generative music 
 evolve at an extraordinary pace. What began as experiments in university l
 abs has become technology that anyone can access from a laptop or phone.\n
 In this session\, you'll trace the rapid evolution of generative music fro
 m early computer experiments through to modern AI platforms\, discover the
  key innovations that made today's tools possible\, and explore where this
  technology might be heading next.\nDrop-in. No registration required.\nTh
 is program is part of the Innovator in Residence (AI and Music Production)
  program\, which is designed to help beginner and intermediate learners bu
 ild knowledge and creative skills and get hands-on with current AI tools i
 n music production and learn about the history\, copyright and ethics of g
 enerative music. For more information and a full list of programs\, visit\
 ntpl.ca/airesident\n.
LOCATION:Fairview\, Room 201\, 2nd Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a201c84dacf581ff7e6743
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Make a Song for Someone You Love
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260525T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260525T160000
UID:69a20220491b809c6f1cfd89@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Have you ever wished you could write a song for a friend's bir
 thday\, create a musical thank-you for someone special\, or surprise a lov
 ed one with a one-of-a-kind melody? You don't need any musical training - 
 today's AI tools let you create original music simply by describing what y
 ou want in everyday language.\nIn this beginner-friendly session\, you'll 
 learn how to use free AI music tools to create short\, personalized songs 
 and musical messages. Whether it's a heartfelt love song\, a funny birthda
 y tune\, or a musical inside joke to share with a friend\, you'll walk awa
 y with something you made yourself - and the know-how to make more. No com
 puter or music experience is required.\nThis program is part of the Innova
 tor in Residence (AI and Music Production) program\, which is designed to 
 help beginner and intermediate learners build knowledge and creative skill
 s and get hands-on with current AI tools in music production and learn abo
 ut the history\, copyright and ethics of generative music. For more inform
 ation and a full list of programs\, visit\ntpl.ca/airesident\n.
LOCATION:Fairview\, Room 201\, 2nd Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a20220491b809c6f1cfd89
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Investigative Tension: Compose True Crime Soundtracks with AI Tool
 s
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260527T160000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260527T180000
UID:69a202588089f23c675eb015@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:True crime is one of the most popular genres in podcasts\, doc
 umentaries\, and streaming television - and the music that drives these st
 ories plays a huge role in building suspense and keeping audiences on the 
 edge of their seats.\nIn this hands-on workshop\, you'll break down what m
 akes an effective true crime soundtrack tick\, then use AI tools to compos
 e your own investigative tension track from scratch. The focus will be on 
 using AI as an assistant while keeping you in the driver's seat as the cre
 ative decision-maker. No prior music or programming experience is require
 d.\nRegistration is required.\nThis program is part of the Innovator in Re
 sidence (AI and Music Production) program\, which is designed to help begi
 nner and intermediate learners build knowledge and creative skills and get
  hands-on with current AI tools in music production and learn about the hi
 story\, copyright and ethics of generative music. For more information and
  a full list of programs\, visit\ntpl.ca/airesident\n.
LOCATION:Fairview\, Digital Innovation Hub\, 3rd Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a202588089f23c675eb015
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:From Our Mouths to Your Ears: Generate Music from Sound with AI To
 ols
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260601T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260601T160000
UID:69a202864dacf581ff7e6766@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:What if you could hum a melody\, tap a rhythm on a table\, or 
 beatbox a groove - and have AI turn it into a fully produced piece of musi
 c? Some of today's AI music tools can interpret sounds you make with your 
 voice and body and transform them into original compositions.\nIn this hig
 h-energy session\, you'll sing\, clap\, beatbox\, and tap your way into cr
 eating music using nothing but your own sounds as a starting point. It's o
 ne of the fastest and most fun ways to go from an idea in your head to a f
 inished track. No musical training is required\; just a willingness to mak
 e some noise.\nThis program is part of the Innovator in Residence (AI and 
 Music Production) program\, which is designed to help beginner and interme
 diate learners build knowledge and creative skills and get hands-on with c
 urrent AI tools in music production and learn about the history\, copyrigh
 t and ethics of generative music. For more information and a full list of 
 programs\, visit\ntpl.ca/airesident\n.
LOCATION:Fairview\, Digital Innovation Hub\, 3rd Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a202864dacf581ff7e6766
