BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Richard III: Discovered and Uncovered
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260506T190000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260506T200000
UID:69b47146ad384e40edb42b46@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:In 2012\, an archaeological dig found the remains of a long lo
 st medieval king. Sheilah O’Connor of the Richard III Society explains w
 hy a woman risked ridicule in her quest to find this controversial monarch
 . And then\, how mitochondria DNA\, X-Rays and a Canadian connection tell 
 a different story about this man.\nSheilah O’Connor is a retired librari
 an and a member of the Canadian Branch of the Richard III Society. She is 
 a semi-regular writer for the Society’s publications. Sheilah has been s
 peaking about Richard III for over 20 years. Audiences have included high 
 school students\, members of various Historical Associations and attendees
  at the Stratford Festival. She was in Leicester during the week that Rich
 ard III was reburied\, and watched the event on a big screen in a square n
 ear the cathedral\nBooks and Media on Richard III\nNon-fiction books\nThe 
 Last Days of Richard III\nThe King's Grave\nThe Princes in the Tower\nRich
 ard III\nFiction books\nThis Son of York\nThe Sunne in Splendour\nThe Daug
 hter of Time\nRequiem of the Rose King\nFilm\nThe Lost King\nThe White Que
 en\nResurrecting Richard III
LOCATION:Deer Park\, Upstairs in room 204
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69b47146ad384e40edb42b46
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Harm Reduction in Toronto: A Panel Discussion on Community\, Servi
 ces\, and Misconceptions.
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260425T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260425T160000
UID:69bb33ed491b809c6f2178f1@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Join community health workers & advocates for a guided convers
 ation about harm reduction.\nHarm reduction is an approach that meets peop
 le where they are using evidence-based methods for reducing health risks a
 ssociated with substance use.\nOur discussion will cover resources\, polic
 ies and services in Toronto that affect people who use drugs. We will chat
  about specific local issues\, and discuss practical ways that we can supp
 ort our community.\nRefreshments will be provided and ingredient lists wil
 l be available.\nPanel speakers include:\nRay Clark\nis a health promotor 
 and educator with Parkdale Queen West Community Health Centre and HART (Ho
 melessness & Addiction Recovery & Treatment) Hub\, previously Parkdale Sup
 ervised Consumption and Treatment Service (CTS). Ray has 20 years of exper
 ience in harm reduction roles. He teaches Harm Reduction and Advanced Over
 dose Response.\nKeyanna Vanloo\nis a case manager with the AMANI program a
 t TAIBU Community Health Centre dedicated to supporting Black youth in a c
 ulturally responsive care environment navigating mental health and/or subs
 tance use challenges.\nJen la Fauci Gordon\nis an Overdose Response Traine
 r and community advocate with Harm Reduction Advocacy Collective (HRAC) To
 ronto. HRAC is a drug-user and community-led advocacy group. Jen identifie
 s as a Person Who Uses Drugs (PWUD)\, and Naloxone saved her life.
LOCATION:North York Central Library\, Auditorium on the 2nd floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69bb33ed491b809c6f2178f1
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
