UID:69bd76afbf48d63c596c382b@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Everything old is new again\, and native plant gardens are now
  all the rage. And for a good reason! A Toronto Master Gardener will go ov
 er:\n- Why native plants are best adapted to (thus more successful in) our
  climatic conditions\;\n- How they support biodiversity by providing food 
 and shelter for birds and pollinators\n- How they enhance the beauty of ou
 r gardens.\nYou have everything to gain and nothing to lose by adding more
  native plants to your garden… come and learn how!\nThis program is part
  of TPL's Our Fragile Planet program series\, supported by Friends of Toro
 nto Public Library\, South Chapter.\nNo registration required.\nDROP-IN!
LOCATION:Rexdale
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69bd76afbf48d63c596c382b
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Dystopia Nonfiction Book Club: How Fascism Works
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260511T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260511T153000
UID:69bd9aa74dacf581ff835dec@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Join us each month to discuss issues in politics and society\,
  and explore how powerful forces are exploiting our world and dystopian im
 aginings are becoming present-day realities.\nMay's book is\nHow Fascism W
 orks: The Politics of Us and Them\nby philosopher Jason Stanley. Copies
  of the book are available to borrow in\nprint\n\,\neBook\n\, and\neAudiob
 ook\nformats. Book club attendees are encouraged to read the book in adv
 ance of the meeting.\nHow Fascism Works\n“identifies ten pillars of fasc
 ist politics—an appeal to the mythic past\, propaganda\, anti-intellectu
 alism\, unreality\, hierarchy\, victimhood\, law and order\, sexual anxiet
 y\, favoring “the heartland\,” and a dismantling of public goods and u
 nions—that amount to an urgent diagnosis of the tactics right-wing polit
 icians use to break down democracies.” By analyzing recent events in Hun
 gary\, Poland\, India\, Myanmar\, and the United States\, among other nati
 ons\, “Stanley uncovers disturbing patterns that are as prevalent today 
 as ever\, and reveals that the stuff of politics—rhetoric and myth—can
  become policy and reality all too quickly. Only by recognizing them\, he 
 argues\, can we begin to resist their most harmful effects and return to d
 emocratic ideals.”\nDrop in. No registration required.
LOCATION:Toronto Reference Library\, Discussion Room\, 3rd Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69bd9aa74dacf581ff835dec
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
