BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:The Life and Art of Mashel Teitelbaum
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260514T130000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260514T143000
UID:69c43e66491b809c6f22e5d5@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:One of Canada’s most talented and influential artistic outsi
 ders\, and the son of Jewish immigrants\, Mashel Teitelbaum grew up during
  the Great Depression\, World War II\, and the Holocaust\, before honing h
 is voice under the likes of Clyfford Still\, Ad Reinhardt\, and Max Beckma
 nn. Teitelbaum created a body of work that remains arresting to this day. 
 From landscapes to portraits\, expressionistic abstraction to conceptual i
 nstallations\, his art was characterized by self-expression and a desire t
 o speak truth to power\, often placing him in conflict with the establishm
 ent. Join curator Andrew Kear for an illustrated presentation\, followed 
 by book sales and signings.\nPresented in partnership with Toronto Public
  Library as part of its Jewish Heritage Series\, and the Canadian Jewish L
 iterary Awards.\nJoin us in the Al Green Theatre\, on Zoom simulcast\, or 
 register to receive the recording.\nAbout this event’s guests:\nAndrew K
 ear\nis Senior Curator and Head of Collections\, Exhibitions\, and Program
 s at Museum London. He was formerly the Head of Collections and Exhibitio
 ns and Curator of Canadian Art at the Winnipeg Art Gallery. Kear began hi
 s career at the Tom Thomson Art Gallery in Owen Sound\, and has taught Can
 adian Art at the University of Winnipeg. He has also published widely\, in
 cluding the 2017 Art Canada Institute publication of\nWilliam Kurelek (192
 7-1977)\n.\nHis curatorial efforts include\nWilliam Kurelek: The Messenger
 \n(2011)\n\,\nStorm and Spirit: The Eckhardt-Gramatté Collection of Germa
 n Expressionist Art\n(2013)\,\nDali Up Close\n(2014)\,\nKarel Funk\n(2016)
 \,\nThe 80s Image\n(2018) and\nRealisms: Canadian Art\, 1850 to the Presen
 t\n(2020). Andrew’s writing has been published in\nCanadian Art\n\,\nBor
 der Crossings\n\, and\nSculpture\n.\n***\nThis event is part of our signat
 ure\nSalon Series\n\, where we host local and international authors\, arti
 sts and thinkers in conversation about their new books and big ideas.\nIt 
 is also part of our programming series\,\nJewish Heritage\n\,\ncreated in 
 collaboration with\nMiles Nadal - Jewish Community Centre\n. Join us in ce
 lebrating the diversity that strengthens our community and makes our city 
 a more vibrant and inclusive place for all.\n***\nPLAN YOUR VISIT:\nLocati
 on:\nAl Green Theatre\, Miles Nadal Jewish Community Centre\, 750 Spadina 
 Ave.\nTime:\nDoors open 12:30pm\, Event begins 1:00pm\nTickets:\nFree regi
 stration required.\nTicket policy:\nWe oversell these events to ensure tha
 t the greatest number of people have an opportunity to attend. Tickets gua
 ranteed until 6:45pm or until capacity is reached. Seating first come\, fi
 rst served.\n***\nInformation Collection Notice:\nThe personal information
  on this form is collected by the Toronto Public Library under the Public 
 Libraries Act\, sections 20(a)\, 20(c)\, and 20(d). The information will o
 nly be used for event and program registration\, delivery and evaluation. 
 Registrants may be contacted to fill out a brief survey following the prog
 ram. Questions about how the library handles your information can be direc
 ted to Answerline staff at answerline@tpl.ca\, 416-397-5981\, 789 Yonge St
 reet\, Toronto ON M4W 2G8.
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69c43e66491b809c6f22e5d5
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
