BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Modern Fairy Tales on Film: Pan's Labyrinth
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260424T120000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260424T130000
UID:69c444e01e64afd01e64b449@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:In this continuation of Toronto Public Library's virtual serie
 s on Modern Fairy Tales on Film\, host Adam Nayman explores\nPan's Labyrin
 th\n\, the dark fantasy of Guillermo Del Toro\, which premiered to critica
 l acclaim and popular success in 2006. Set against the nightmarish backdro
 p of Francoist Spain\, the film centres upon the adventurous Ofelia\, a ch
 ild who discovers the titular overgrown labyrinth\, and strikes up a begui
 ling relationship with a mysterious faun. The story is a springboard for s
 ome of Del Toro's most audacious flights of fancy\, combining animatronics
  with CGI to create a singular visual masterpiece. Along with critic Soray
 a Sebghati and author Silvia Moreno-Garcia\, Nayman will navigate the twis
 ted byways of this maze-like masterpiece\, all the way to the heart of its
  mythical allure.\nABOUT THIS EVENT'S GUESTS:\nSoraya Sebghati\nis\nan L.A
 .-born-and-raised film critic\nand the front woman of the local band Night
  Talks. Her writing on film can be found on her\nSubstack\n.\nSilvia Moren
 o-Garcia\nis the author of\nThe Bewitching\n\,\nThe Seventh Veil of Salome
 \, The Daughter of Doctor Moreau\n\,\nMexican Gothic\n\, and many other bo
 oks. She has won the Locus\, British Fantasy and World Fantasy awards.\nAd
 am Nayman\nis a critic\, teacher\, and author\, whose books include critic
 al surveys of the Coen Brothers\, Paul Thomas Anderson\, and most recently
 \, in\nMind Games\n\, the filmmaker David Fincher. He is a regular contrib
 utor to\nThe Ringer\n\, a lecturer at the University of Toronto's Cinema S
 tudies Institute\, and he has written on film for\nThe New Yorker\nand\nTh
 e New York Times\n.\n***\nImportant information for accessing this live vi
 rtual event:\nYou must register for a free ticket via Eventbrite to gain a
 ccess to this event.\nThis event will be presented in a Zoom Webinar. Once
  registered\, you will receive reminder emails from both Zoom and Eventbri
 te with links and instructions to access your unique Zoom Webinar link to 
 watch this event.\nAt the time of the event\, you must be signed in to Zoo
 m or Eventbrite with the same email address that you used to book your tic
 ket in order to access your unique event link. Unique event links can only
  be open on one device at a time.\n***\nAccessibility at Toronto Public Li
 brary\nWe are committed to making our content accessible to as many Toront
 onians as possible. Please call or email us if you are Deaf or have a disa
 bility and would like to request accommodation to participate in this prog
 ram. Please let us know as far in advance as possible and we will do our b
 est to meet your request. At least three weeks' notice is preferred. Phone
  416-393-7099 or email accessibleservices@tpl.ca
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69c444e01e64afd01e64b449
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Write AI Prompts to Get the Music You Want
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260415T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260415T160000
UID:69a1ff431e64afd01e5e9069@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Describing music in words has always been a challenge - what e
 xactly does "warm" or "dreamy" or "punchy" sound like? When you're using A
 I to create music\, the words you choose make all the difference between g
 etting something magical and getting something that misses the mark entire
 ly.\nIn this session\, you'll discover why music is so hard to describe\, 
 then put that knowledge to work by experimenting with different prompting 
 techniques to see how accurately you can guide AI toward the sound in your
  head. You'll also learn advanced strategies\, including how to use one AI
  to help you write better instructions for another. No prior music or prog
 ramming experience is required.\nRegistration is required.\nThis program i
 s part of the Innovator in Residence (AI and Music Production) program\, w
 hich is designed to help beginner and intermediate learners build knowledg
 e and creative skills and get hands-on with current AI tools in music prod
 uction and learn about the history\, copyright and ethics of generative mu
 sic. For more information and a full list of programs\, visit tpl.ca/aires
 ident.
LOCATION:Fairview\, Digital Innovation Hub\, 3rd Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a1ff431e64afd01e5e9069
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Mix and Master Music with AI Tools
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260428T180000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260428T200000
UID:69a200a94dacf581ff7e66c5@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:You've written a great song\, but why doesn't it sound like th
 e music you hear on the radio or your favourite streaming playlist? The an
 swer usually comes down to mixing and mastering\, the final stages of musi
 c production that give a track its polish and professional sound.\nThese w
 ere actually the first areas of music production where AI tools proved the
 mselves\, because much of the process involves technical decisions that ca
 n be measured and optimized. In this session\, you'll learn what mixing an
 d mastering are\, why they matter\, and how AI tools can help you achieve 
 professional-quality results in a fraction of the time. No prior music or
  programming experience is required.\nThis program is part of the Innovato
 r in Residence (AI and Music Production) program\, which is designed to he
 lp beginner and intermediate learners build knowledge and creative skills 
 and get hands-on with current AI tools in music production and learn about
  the history\, copyright and ethics of generative music. For more informat
 ion and a full list of programs\, visit tpl.ca/airesident.
LOCATION:Fairview\, Digital Innovation Hub\, 3rd Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a200a94dacf581ff7e66c5
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Worlds of Music: Write AI Prompts for Different Music Styles
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260502T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260502T160000
UID:69a2013e1e64afd01e5e90a9@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Music comes in an incredible variety of styles from cultures a
 round the world\, but most AI music tools have been trained primarily on W
 estern music traditions. So what happens when you want to create something
  different?\nIn this session\, you'll explore the musical building blocks 
 that define different styles from around the globe\, including scales\, rh
 ythms\, and structures that may be unfamiliar to Western ears. Then you'll
  experiment with prompting techniques to see how far you can push AI tools
  beyond their comfort zone. Some experiments will succeed\, some won't\, a
 nd both outcomes will teach you something valuable about the possibilities
  and limitations of today's AI music technology. No prior music or progra
 mming experience is required. Participants are encouraged to bring example
 s of music they’d like to explore.\nRegistration is required.\nThis prog
 ram is part of the Innovator in Residence (AI and Music Production) progra
 m\, which is designed to help beginner and intermediate learners build kno
 wledge and creative skills and get hands-on with current AI tools in music
  production and learn about the history\, copyright and ethics of generati
 ve music. For more information and a full list of programs\, visit\ntpl.ca
 /airesident\n.
LOCATION:Fairview\, Digital Innovation Hub\, 3rd Floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69a2013e1e64afd01e5e90a9
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
