BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Kids & Parents Book Club
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T150000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T160000
UID:69c57e8a8089f23c6764cff8@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Our book for the month of April is The Folk of the Faraway Tre
 e by Enid Blyton.\nWhen family friend\, Connie\, visits\, neither Joe\, Be
 th nor Frannie are impressed. Connie is bossy and also refuses to believe 
 in the Magic Faraway Tree—until she meets Moon-Face\, Saucepan Man and S
 ilky the fairy! When the Faraway Tree starts to fade\, even Connie is worr
 ied. What can they do to save it?\nEnid Blyton was one of the world's most
  popular children's authors\, and also the most translated author in histo
 ry.\nCopies of the book are available at the library.\nThe Folk of the Far
 away Tree
LOCATION:Mimico Centennial\, Meeting Room
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69c57e8a8089f23c6764cff8
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Navigating Cancer Treatment Decisions with Confidence
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260423T190000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260423T200000
UID:69c580d19057005337d08aa6@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:Making decisions about cancer treatment can feel overwhelming\
 , whether facing a new diagnosis or managing recurrent disease. This sessi
 on offers clear\, supportive information to help individuals and families 
 prepare for conversations with their care team and approach treatment deci
 sions with greater confidence and clarity.\nWhat to Expect:\nUnderstanding
  Your Care Options:\nLearn about factors that may influence your treatment
  decisions and how to approach them.\nFinding Reliable Information:\nBecom
 e more familiar with your diagnosis and available treatment options\, incl
 uding where to access trusted information.\nBuilding Your Support System:\
 nIdentify people and services that can support you throughout your care jo
 urney.\nPreparing for Appointments:\nLearn how to prepare helpful question
 s so you can communicate your concerns and preferences effectively.\nSuppo
 rting Caregivers:\nExplore the important role caregivers play in treatment
  decision-making and how they can offer meaningful support.\nFocusing on W
 hat Matters Most:\nReflect on your values and priorities when evaluating d
 ifferent treatment options.\nAbout the Speaker\nThis session will be led b
 y Lisa Malinowski Kamran (she/her)\, Registered Social Worker (MSW\, RSW) 
 and Membership and Outreach Coordinator at Gilda’s Toronto. Drawing on h
 er experience in social work\, mindfulness\, and community-based health in
 itiatives\, she will share practical tools and guidance to support informe
 d and compassionate decision-making during cancer care.\nThis program is p
 resented by Toronto Public Library in collaboration with the West Toronto 
 Ontario Health Team (OHT)\, a network of over 40 local health and social s
 ervice providers working together to improve the health and well-being of 
 communities in West Toronto.\nYour Health Matters\nThis program is part of
  Toronto Public Library’s\nYour Health Matters\ninitiative\, which offer
 s trusted health programs and resources to help people make informed decis
 ions about their health. Learn more by exploring the\nYour Health Matters 
 web page\n.\nReserve Your Spot Today!\nThis virtual event is free to join 
 but registration is required.\nPlease register on Eventbrite\n.\nOnce regi
 stered\, you’ll receive an email with details on how to join the session
 .\nWe can’t wait to see you there!
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69c580d19057005337d08aa6
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Writers Collective of Canada (WCC): Community Writing Workshop
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260502T100000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260502T113000
UID:69c58197b48451fc3c0b7524@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:When we write with others\, we discover ourselves\n.\nWCC work
 shops offer a brave creative space where all are welcomed to write and exp
 lore their story in a space free of critique.\nThe workshops are led by tr
 ained volunteer facilitators who also act as participants. The group write
 s in response to prompts\, is invited to share their first draft writing a
 nd offer affirming feedback to one another.\nWhile the focus is on the pro
 cess of writing rather than a finished product - the stories that emerge i
 n WCC workshops are magnificent. In sharing and listening to one another's
  stories\, participants find connection with self and others.\nNo experien
 ce required. Beginners are welcome. All materials are provided.\nInformati
 on Collection Notice:\nThe personal information on this form is collected 
 by the Toronto Public Library under the Public Libraries Act\, sections 20
 (a)\, 20(c)\, and 20(d). The information will only be used for event and p
 rogram registration\, delivery and evaluation. Questions about how the lib
 rary handles your information can be directed to Answerline staff at\nansw
 erline@tpl.ca\n\, 416-397-5981\, 789 Yonge Street\, Toronto ON M4W 2G8.
LOCATION:Gerrard/Ashdale\, 2nd Floor Program Room
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69c58197b48451fc3c0b7524
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
