BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Journalism Series with David Silverberg: What you need to know abo
 ut Canadian media today
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260506T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260506T193000
UID:69c81fe8b48451fc3c0bd8f2@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:This lecture is presented by the North York Central Library's
  2026 Writer in Residence David Silverberg\, whose focus is on Journalism.
 \nEvery journalist should be aware of the shifting landscape in Canadian m
 edia. As many print magazines and regional newspapers shutter for good\, i
 nnovative and bold news networks thriving online are filling the gap. Edit
 ors are looking for articles on topics you wouldn’t read years ago wheth
 er in science\, technology\, the arts or sports. You’ll find out the kin
 d of engaging articles freelance journalists can write for these outlets.\
 nThis lecture will be followed by Q&A\nLearn more about TPL's\nWriter in R
 esidence\nprogram\, including upcoming programs and one-on-one consultatio
 n sessions.\nInformation Collection Notice:\nThe personal information on t
 his form is collected by the Toronto Public Library under the Public Libra
 ries Act\, sections 20(a)\, 20(c)\, and 20(d). The information will only b
 e used for event and program registration\, delivery and evaluation. Quest
 ions about how the library handles your information can be directed to Ans
 werline staff at\nanswerline@tpl.ca\n\, 416-397-5981\, 789 Yonge Street\, 
 Toronto ON M4W 2G8.
LOCATION:North York Central Library\, Room 101\, 1st floor
URL:https://tpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/events/69c81fe8b48451fc3c0bd8f2
X-SOURCE:Toronto Public Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Journalism Series with David Silverberg: How to pitch your article
  ideas to editors
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260512T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260512T193000
UID:69c81fe8b48451fc3c0bd8f3@tpl.bibliocommons.com
DESCRIPTION:This lecture is presented by the North York Central Library's 
 2026 Writer in Residence David Silverberg\, whose focus is on Journalism.\
 nIf you’ve always wanted to write for a news network\, you’ll want to 
 come to this talk and analysis of what makes a strong pitch. To impress ed
 itors\, a pitch has to include several important journalistic ingredients
 …and your personality. First\, learn how to find story ideas in your com
 munity and beyond. Next\, you’ll be shown how those ideas can turn into 
 compelling pitches. Examples of great (and not so great) pitches will show
  you why certain ideas attract an editor’s attention.\nThis lecture will
  be followed by Q&A\nLearn more about TPL's\nWriter in Residence\nprogram\
 , including upcoming programs and one-on-one consultation sessions.\nInfor
 mation Collection Notice:\nThe personal information on this form is collec
 ted by the Toronto Public Library under the Public Libraries Act\, section
